:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For many industrial sectors, including steel and cement production, CCS is the only technology that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> enable large-scale emi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssions reductions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">According to the National Audit Office, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nnovation in CCS has the potential to lead to hundreds of billions of savings to the UK economy by 2050</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="I" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our response, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognise the success of the Government’s current approach to funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">low carbon innovation. Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has supported a large number of CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R&amp;D </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">projects to date, we feel that further improvements can be made by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Focusing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding for innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on those areas which have the greatest potential to reduce costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and spe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed-up large scale deployment of CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, e.g. full chain demonstration, shared CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> transport infrastructure and characterisation of storage sites</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Adopting a more coordinated and collaborative approach to R&amp;D, ensuring that the R&amp;D community consistently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">addresses the priorities of industry and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the results of research are fed back into projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and,</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increasing the number of demonstration plants to include other power generation technologies and integration with industrial emitters (cluster development)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CCSA brings together a wide range of specialist companies across the spectrum of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Carbon Capture &amp; Storage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">technology, as well as a variety of support services to the energy sector. The Association exists to represent the interests of its members in promoting the business of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and to assist policy developments in the UK and the EU towards a long term regulato</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ry framework for CCS, as a means of abating carbon dioxide emissions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the opportunity to respond to the Energy and Climate Change Committee inquir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y into low carbon innovation and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recognise the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">importance of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> meet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> legally-binding climate chang</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e targets in the most cost-effective manner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We believe CCS will have a major role to play in achieving this objective. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Evidence suggests that CCS will be essential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the UK to meet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">legally-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">binding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">climate change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">targets at lowest possible cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chnology </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nnovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eeds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssessment (TINA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for CCS shows that innovation in CCS will potentially lead to “hundreds of billions” of savings to the UK by 2050</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is supported by ETI analysis which shows that, without CCS in the mix, delivering low-carbo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n energy in the UK in 2050 will be £30-40 billion more expensive per year (equivalent to 1% of GDP)</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has a vital role to play in securing the future of energy intensive industries in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Energy intensive industries currently employ 160,000 p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eople directly in the UK with an additional 800,000 jobs indirectly supported through supply chains, etc.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For many industries, e.g. steel and cement production, CCS is the only technology that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deliver the large scale emissions reductions necessary – as their CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as fuel-generated. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be critical to ensuring that these industries can decarbonise in a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cost-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">competitive manner. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CCSA supports t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Government’s commitment to funding low carbon innovation and commends the Department for Energy and Climate Change in its efforts to foster innovation in CCS. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NAO report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on public funding for innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">shows that public spending on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS innovation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eclined by nearly 50% between 2010-11 and 2011-12</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This decline is significantly greater than the average 33% reduction across all low carbon technologies and will need to be reversed if Government is to realise its indicative vision of ‘up to 12 GW of CC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S by 2030’ (as identified in the response to the CCS Cost Reduction Taskforce report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and referenced in DECC 2030 scenarios</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">).</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CCSA Response to selected questions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Will the Government’s current approach towards low carbon innovation help to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">achieve the UK’s legally binding targets at lowest possible cost?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">– Are the Government and LCICG targeting investment towards the most effective stages of the innovation process, including over the longer term?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nnovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is absolutely cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">itical to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the successful deployment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and cost-reduction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of low carbon technologies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">echnolog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> innovation, policy innovation, financial innovation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">successful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">demonstration of full-chain projects will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">needed to ensure the developm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent of a commercial CCS industry in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> At the same time, technology transfer from other industries (eg. agri-chemicals, petrochemicals, and refineries) should be welcomed as it introduces a degree of ‘proven-ness’ into what is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">otherwise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an emergent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The government, within EMR, has recognised the need for on-going incentives for CCS alongside those for other types of low carbon electricity generation, a world-first for CCS. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite this, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> currently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> lacks certainty as to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e expected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deployment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trajectory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> beyond the planned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommercialisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme and,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">because it cannot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> estimate when it may achieve pay-back</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">finds it difficult to plan and justify its RD&amp;D. This is a major challenge to achieving the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">objectives of the Government.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In March 2012 the Government established the CCS Cost Reduction Taskforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (CRTF)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to identify opportunities for cost reduction across the CCS chain to achieve cost competitive CCS in the 2020s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The Final Report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> published in May 2013</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">showed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that innovation in capture technology, including engineering design and performance improvements, could lead to cost reductions of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">around 10%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by 2030</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> based on current technologies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When considering second and third </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">generation capture technologies, this figure could be greatly increased, however t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his can only be achieved however if the underlying conditions – many of which are not a factor of technological innovation – are put in place to enable the successful deploym</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent of CCS.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s current approach to funding l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ow carbon innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has provided £20 million of support in the current Spending Review period (2011-2015) for CCS projects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and, to date,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supported 14 projects</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In addition, another 100 pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ojects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supported through the Government’s £125 million 4-year CCS R&amp;D Programme. Combined with the Government’s £1 billion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS Commercialisation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rogramme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (current competition)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and with the introduction of the Contracts-for-Difference (CfD) Feed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-in Tariff for CCS projects under the Electricity Market Reform (EMR), we feel that current levels of Government support for CCS innovation are amongst the best in the world.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="f