ost impetus due to a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">follow-on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> funding. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that the Government’s current approach to funding innovation for CCS could be improved by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adopting additional measures to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research projects consiste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntly address the priorities of industry, e.g. through increased collaboration. It is equally important to ensure that research/innovation is demonstrably achieving its objective of bringing technologies closer to commercial deployment, and we would support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> any additional efforts to ensure that this objective is consistently met.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the current approach towards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">innovation does not recognise the importance of reducing emissions from energy intensive industries. In the UK, and across Europe, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many industries are coming under increasing pressure to decarbonise and are at risk of compromising global competitiveness as a result. For </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">various</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">industrial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sectors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such as steel and cement production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, CCS is the only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">technology capable of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delivering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emissions reductions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (because CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is process as well as fuel-generated)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and it is imperative that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policies are developed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to reduce the cost of CCS for such operations. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> – Does the Government have the right balance of focus betwe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">en energy efficiency, renewable energy and other low carbon technologies?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst the CCSA agree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that a package through which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">energy efficiency, renewables and other low carbon technologies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are supported is necessary in order to meet Government objectives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we would suggest that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> funding for energy innovation c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould be allocated in line with the 3-way split under the Electricity Market Reform, i.e. nuclear, renewables and CCS.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further to paragraph 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, we would consider renewables </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a form of low carbon technology and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">refore question why renewables are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> being addressed as a distinct area. In continuing with the current balance of focus, there is a danger that focus on renewables could have a detrimental impact on funding for other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">low carbon technologies.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">take this opportunity to remind the Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that CCS technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particularly in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> stage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> requires energy input and therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whilst dramatically reducing CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emissions, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> increase the energy intensity o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">industrial processes and power genera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it is applied to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is essential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in energy efficiency is not pursued in such a way as to discourage investment in CCS.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For industrial sectors where CCS offers the only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">means of significantly reducing CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emissions (for example, steel production), there is a distinct lack of research and innovation on CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">because of a) the absence of transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and storage infrastructure, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> b) the high costs of full chain projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, i.e. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capture, transport and storage of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We would suggest therefore that additional funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be allocated to innovation in transport and storage processes and technologies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By taking a more holistic view of innovation, and recognising the role of innovation i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n transport and storage infrastructure delivery, we believe that innovations in capture technology </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for all potential applications </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could be more quickly realis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed and brought to market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We look forward to seeing the results of the DECC/BiS industrial CCS te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chno-economic study (due in March 2014) which will hopefully tease out some of the innovation needs for CCS across a variety of industrial sectors</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">– How is the Government maximizing opportunities to learn from and partner with international </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">partners within and beyond the EU?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CCSA believes that new innovations in CCS can be achieved through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continued and improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> knowledge sharing at an international level. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Global CCS Institute (GCCSI) lists 20 ‘active’ CCS projects across the world</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, none of which are in the UK. In 2014, the world’s first large scale CCS projects on coal-fired power plant will come into operation at Boundary Dam (Saskatchewan, Canada) and Kemper County </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Mississippi, United States). Whilst a number of projects are in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the early stages of development in the UK, including those being considered in the Government’s £1 billion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Commercialisation P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rogramme, the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">no longer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consider itself </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the leader on CCS that it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">claimed to be a few years ago</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite losing leadershi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p on CCS deployment, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a number of areas where the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">remains at the forefront and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">share its experience of CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> international partners, including:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Experience regarding the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Contract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s-for-Difference Feed-in Tariff </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Electricity Market Reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the world’s first long-term sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">port mechanism for CCS projects;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Knowledge from the previous CCS competition and Longannet and Kingsnorth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Front End Engineering Design (FEED) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">studies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which is available but nei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ther easy to access or digest; and,</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FEED </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contracts for the two projects being suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ted through the current CCS competition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expected to impose significant knowledge transfer obligations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on developers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a way of accelerating innovation and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deployment of CCS in the UK, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e believe that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government support c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould be extended to RD&amp;D projects which may executed abroad but still support the objectives of the UK Roadmap and the development of the CCS industry in the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="f